<Base title="Substrate" description="Repeatable automation patterns for codebases. Audits, scaffolds, standards, workflows, and a self-reinforcing proposal pipeline.">
  <h1>Substrate</h1>
  <p>
    Substrate is a framework for codifying the repeatable patterns of a healthy
    codebase: audits, scaffolds, standards, AI-driven workflows, and a
    self-reinforcing proposal pipeline that watches its own runs and proposes
    improvements to the conventions it just executed.
  </p>

  <h2>Why substrate</h2>
  <p>
    Every team accumulates opinions about how its codebase should be audited,
    how new services should scaffold, what standards reviews enforce. Most
    teams leave those opinions in shell scripts and tribal knowledge.
    Substrate ships the framework so those opinions become<em> the
    framework</em>: scaffolded into your repo at <code>substrate init</code>,
    edited in place, then upgraded with a real three-way merge as the
    framework evolves.
  </p>

  <h2>Install</h2>
  <pre><code>npx @op4z/substrate@latest init</code></pre>
  <p>
    See the <a href="/quick-start/">Quick Start</a> for the full first-run
    walkthrough.
  </p>

  <h2>Status</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>v2.0 (current):</strong> AI-orchestrated workflow runtime, cross-cutting hooks, conditional doc-checks, first-class memory, proposal pipeline (drift detection → applicators → review walker), schedule trigger, plural knowledge sources.</li>
    <li><strong>v1.0:</strong> 35-rule audit detector runtime, 21 opinionated standards docs, three AI bridges (Claude Code, Cursor, MCP), telemetry opt-in, true three-way upgrade.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Headline features (v2.0)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Workflow manifest runtime.</strong> Declare a workflow once
      (manifest YAML + prose body), invoke it via
      <code>substrate run &lt;workflow&gt;</code>, and substrate orchestrates
      context loading, step execution, and exit gating. Three reference
      templates ship: <code>tackle-task</code>, <code>audit-service</code>,
      <code>audit-package</code>. <a href="/workflows/">More →</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Self-reinforcing proposal pipeline.</strong> Every run emits
      a session-event log. Drift detectors watch for ad-hoc steps, skipped
      steps, repeated prompts, recurring rule violations. Findings classify
      into eight proposal types that an applicator can write back to your
      workflow / rules / standards / memory.
      <strong>The headline primitive of v2.0.</strong>
      <a href="/proposals/">More →</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cross-cutting hooks.</strong> One YAML file declares "fire this
      hook on every workflow completion when X" — applies to every workflow
      without per-workflow copy-paste. Default hooks cover sidecar emission,
      trend updates, task proposal, and drift detection.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Conditional doc-checks.</strong> Registry of "if commit
      message matches <code>feat:</code>, require <code>CHANGELOG.md</code>"
      checks. Used as a deterministic pre-commit / pre-merge gate.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>First-class memory.</strong> Read Claude Code's
      <code>MEMORY.md</code> directory by default; filter by type / scope /
      tags / changed-file overlap; inject into workflow context.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Plural knowledge sources.</strong> docker-compose +
      Kubernetes + env-registry built-in; custom plugins ship third-party
      inputs into the same <code>auto/docs/KNOWLEDGE.md</code> render.
      <a href="/knowledge-sources/">More →</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Schedule trigger.</strong> Cron / interval / every-N-commits
      triggers; <code>substrate scheduler --check</code> reports due
      workflows without invoking anything (delegates to your CI / cron /
      AI session).
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Built on the v1.0 foundation</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>35-rule audit detector runtime</strong> covering backend, frontend, security, dependencies, dead-code, and more.</li>
    <li><strong>21 standards docs</strong> as opinionated starting points that <em>you own</em> after init.</li>
    <li><strong>Three AI bridges:</strong> Claude Code, Cursor, MCP (Claude Desktop, Continue, Cline).</li>
    <li><strong>Real three-way merge</strong> on substrate upgrade — your edits + substrate's improvements, reconciled.</li>
    <li><strong>Plugin contracts</strong> for task adapters (Linear / Jira / GitHub Issues) and VCS adapters.</li>
  </ul>
</Base>
